{"id": "e8c320f1-8859-4590-8edd-539b641a6ea8", "timestamp": "2026-06-28T03:20:19.550374", "source": "environment", "tool_name": "file_editor", "tool_call_id": "019f0a86870d33263522eb2fd7087207", "observation": {"content": [{"cache_prompt": false, "type": "text", "text": "Here's the result of running `cat -n` on G:\\research\\01_agents\\swe-e2e\\Bmk-dev\\task\\minikv-realrepo-submit\\prd.md:\n     1\t# MiniKV Public Packet\n     2\t\n     3\t## Overview\n     4\t\n     5\tBuild `minikv.py`, an in-memory data structure store library. It exposes one Python class, `QueueServer`, that stores strings/numbers, lists, sets, and hashes in a single key namespace. Every key has one public type at a time, and all API methods must read and update that same canonical type-tagged state.\n     6\t\n     7\tThe implementation language is Python 3.11. Place `minikv.py` at the root of your solution directory. Use only the Python standard library.\n     8\t\n     9\tPublic API:\n    10\t\n    11\t```python\n    12\tfrom minikv import QueueServer\n    13\t\n    14\tserver = QueueServer(use_gevent=False)\n    15\tserver.kv_set(\"name\", \"Alice\")\n    16\tprint(server.kv_get(\"name\"))       # \"Alice\"\n    17\tprint(server.kv_incr(\"counter\"))   # 1\n    18\tserver.lpush(\"items\", \"a\", \"b\")\n    19\tserver.sadd(\"tags\", \"python\")\n    20\tserver.hset(\"user:1\", \"name\", \"Alice\")\n    21\t```\n    22\t\n    23\tThe benchmark does not inspect private implementation details.\n    24\t\n    25\t## Product Model\n    26\t\n    27\tMiniKV has one canonical fact source: a key namespace where each live key maps to a stored value, a type tag, and optional expiry metadata. The public methods are projections over that fact source:\n    28\t\n    29\t- direct key reads and writes through `kv_get`, `kv_set`, `kv_mget`, `kv_mset`, `kv_delete`, `kv_exists`, and counters;\n    30\t- list views through `lpush`, `rpush`, `lpop`, `rpop`, and `lrange`;\n    31\t- set views through `sadd`, `srem`, `smembers`, and `scard`;\n    32\t- hash views through `hset`, `hget`, `hdel`, and `hgetall`;\n    33\t- lifecycle views through `expire`, `kv_flush`, `save_to_disk`, and `restore_from_disk`.\n    34\t\n    35\tCorrectness is not just that each method works by itself. Mixed operations must keep those projections consistent. For example, if a key was created as a set, then `kv_get`, `smembers`, `scard`, persistence, wrong-type errors, and later deletion must all agree about that same set key.\n    36\t\n    37\t## Feature Set\n    38\t\n    39\tThe product has six feature modules:\n    40\t\n    41\t1. String and scalar key-value operations: `kv_set`, `kv_get`, `kv_delete`, `kv_exists`, `kv_incr`, `kv_decr`.\n    42\t2. Bulk key-value operations: `kv_mset`, `kv_mget`.\n    43\t3. List operations: `lpush`, `rpush`, `lpop`, `rpop`, `lrange`.\n    44\t4. Set operations: `sadd`, `srem`, `smembers`, `scard`.\n    45\t5. Hash operations: `hset`, `hget`, `hdel`, `hgetall`.\n    46\t6. Key management and persistence: `expire`, `kv_flush`, `save_to_disk`, `restore_from_disk`.\n    47\t\n    48\t## Global Invariants\n    49\t\n    50\t- There is one canonical key namespace. A live key has exactly one type tag and every public method must consult that same tag.\n    51\t- A key's type is determined by the operation that created or overwrote it: `dict` values are `HASH`, `list` values are `QUEUE`, `set` values are `SET`, and all other values are `KV`. `lpush`/`rpush` create `QUEUE`, `sadd`/`smembers`/`scard` create `SET`, and `hset`/`hgetall` create `HASH`.\n    52\t- `kv_set` overwrites the previous value, type, and expiry for the key. `kv_delete` removes the value, type, and expiry so the name can be reused with a different type.\n    53\t- Type-restricted operations must raise `CommandError` on wrong-type keys. Failed operations must be atomic: the key's value, type, expiry, existence, type-specific views, and persisted representation must remain unchanged.\n    54\t- `kv_get` is the direct read projection of the stored value. Type-specific methods such as `lrange`, `smembers`, `scard`, `hget`, and `hgetall` must agree with direct reads for the same live key.\n    55\t- `smembers` returns the actual stored set object. Mutating that returned set is reflected in later `smembers`, `scard`, `kv_get`, and persistence.\n    56\t- `hgetall` returns the actual stored dict object. Mutating that returned dict is reflected in later `hgetall`, `hget`, `kv_get`, and persistence.\n    57\t- `expire` sets an absolute timeout for a live key. Expired keys are lazily removed by public operations, and expiry removal clears the key's value and type so the name can be reused.\n    58\t- `kv_flush` removes every live key and its type/expiry metadata. After a flush, direct reads report missing keys and collection APIs behave as they do for missing keys.\n    59\t- `save_to_disk` and `restore_from_disk` round-trip the public semantic state: values, type tags, mutable set/hash contents, counters, and unexpired expiry metadata. A restored server must expose the same direct reads, type-specific views, wrong-type behavior, and later persistence behavior as the original.\n    60\t- State is private to each `QueueServer` instance.\n    61\t\n    62\t## Class: QueueServer\n    63\t\n    64\t### Constructor\n    65\t\n    66\t`QueueServer(use_gevent=False)`\n    67\t\n    68\tCreate a new data store instance. The `use_gevent` parameter can be ignored for this task; always pass `False`.\n    69\t\n    70\t### String and Scalar Operations\n    71\t\n    72\t#### `kv_set(key, value)`\n    73\t\n    74\tStore a value. Returns `1`. The type is auto-detected: `dict` becomes `HASH`, `list` becomes `QUEUE`, `set` becomes `SET`, and anything else becomes `KV`. This overwrites any previous value, type, and expiry for the key.\n    75\t\n    76\t#### `kv_get(key)`\n    77\t\n    78\tReturn the stored value, or `None` if the key does not exist or has expired.\n    79\t\n    80\t#### `kv_delete(key)`\n    81\t\n    82\tRemove the key, including type and expiry metadata. Returns `1` if deleted, `0` if not found.\n    83\t\n    84\t#### `kv_exists(key)`\n    85\t\n    86\tReturn `1` if the key exists and has not expired, otherwise `0`.\n    87\t\n    88\t#### `kv_incr(key)`\n    89\t\n    90\tIncrement a numeric `KV` value by `1`. If the key does not exist, create it at `0` and then increment to `1`. Values of type `int` and `float` are numeric. Strings are not parsed as numbers; incrementing a string value raises `CommandError`. Returns the new value.\n    91\t\n    92\t#### `kv_decr(key)`\n    93\t\n    94\tDecrement a numeric `KV` value by `1`. If the key does not exist, create it at `0` and then decrement to `-1`. It has the same numeric and error semantics as `kv_incr`.\n    95\t\n    96\t### Bulk Operations\n    97\t\n    98\t#### `kv_mset(__data=None, **kwargs)`\n    99\t\n   100\tSet multiple keys from a dict and/or keyword arguments. Each key uses the same type detection and overwrite rules as `kv_set`. Returns the count of keys set.\n   101\t\n   102\t#### `kv_mget(*keys)`\n   103\t\n   104\tReturn a list of direct-read values in the same order as the requested keys. Missing or expired keys appear as `None`.\n   105\t\n   106\t### List Operations\n   107\t\n   108\t#### `lpush(key, *values)`\n   109\t\n   110\tPrepend values to the head of a list. Creates the list if it does not exist. Values are applied in argument order, so `lpush(\"q\", \"a\", \"b\")` leaves `\"b\"` at the head. Returns the number of values pushed.\n   111\t\n   112\t#### `rpush(key, *values)`\n   113\t\n   114\tAppend values to the tail. Creates the list if it does not exist. Returns the number of values pushed.\n   115\t\n   116\t#### `lpop(key)`\n   117\t\n   118\tRemove and return the first element, or `None` if the list is empty or missing.\n   119\t\n   120\t#### `rpop(key)`\n   121\t\n   122\tRemove and return the last element, or `None` if the list is empty or missing.\n   123\t\n   124\t#### `lrange(key, start, end=None)`\n   125\t\n   126\tReturn a list slice using Python slice semantics: `[start:end]`. `None` for `end` means \"to the end\". Missing keys return `[]`. Raises `CommandError` on non-list keys.\n   127\t\n   128\t### Set Operations\n   129\t\n   130\t#### `sadd(key, *members)`\n   131\t\n   132\tAdd members to a set. Creates it if it does not exist. Returns the new cardinality.\n   133\t\n   134\t#### `srem(key, *members)`\n   135\t\n   136\tRemove members. Returns the count of members actually removed. Missing set keys return `0`.\n   137\t\n   138\t#### `smembers(key)`\n   139\t\n   140\tReturn the internal set object. If the key does not exist, create an empty set first. Raises `CommandError` on non-set keys.\n   141\t\n   142\t#### `scard(key)`\n   143\t\n   144\tReturn the cardinality. If the key does not exist, create an empty set and return `0`. Raises `CommandError` on non-set keys.\n   145\t\n   146\t### Hash Operations\n   147\t\n   148\t#### `hset(key, field, value)`\n   149\t\n   150\tSet a field. Creates the hash if it does not exist. Returns `1`.\n   151\t\n   152\t#### `hget(key, field)`\n   153\t\n   154\tReturn the field value, or `None` if the hash or field does not exist. Raises `CommandError` on non-hash keys.\n   155\t\n   156\t#### `hdel(key, field)`\n   157\t\n   158\tDelete a field. Returns `1` if deleted, `0` if not found. Raises `CommandError` on non-hash keys.\n   159\t\n   160\t#### `hgetall(key)`\n   161\t\n   162\tReturn the internal dict object. If the key does not exist, create an empty hash first. Raises `CommandError` on non-hash keys.\n   163\t\n   164\t### Key Management\n   165\t\n   166\t#### `expire(key, nseconds)`\n   167\t\n   168\tSet a timeout in seconds for a live key. Returns `None`. Calling `expire` for a missing key is a no-op.\n   169\t\n   170\t#### `kv_flush()`\n   171\t\n   172\tRemove all live keys and metadata. Returns the number of live keys removed.\n   173\t\n   174\t#### `save_to_disk(filename)`\n   175\t\n   176\tPersist the entire database state to a file using `pickle`. Returns `True`.\n   177\t\n   178\t#### `restore_from_disk(filename)`\n   179\t\n   180\tRestore database state from a pickle file. Returns `True` if restored, `False` if the file does not exist.\n   181\t\n   182\t## Error Behavior\n   183\t\n   184\t- `CommandError` is raised for type mismatches, such as list operations on scalar keys, hash operations on set keys, or set operations on hash keys.\n   185\t- `CommandError` is raised for `kv_incr`/`kv_decr` on non-numeric values, including numeric-looking strings.\n   186\t- Error messages should be descriptive, but exact text is not part of the public API.\n   187\t\n   188\t## Non-Goals\n   189\t\n   190\t- No network server or client protocol. Only the Python class API.\n   191\t- No RESP protocol, gevent integration, or connection handling.\n   192\t- No sorted sets, streams, pub/sub, transactions, or Lua scripting.\n   193\t- No scheduled task queue.\n   194\t\n   195\t## Evaluation Style\n   196\t\n   197\tHidden tests are split into two scores:\n   198\t\n   199\t- Unit tests exercise isolated method contracts with short Python snippets.\n   200\t- System tests exercise cross-view invariants over the canonical type-tagged key namespace.\n   201\t\n   202\tSystem tests are labeled by dimension: `projection_consistency`, `error_atomicity`, `lifecycle_consistency`, `expiry_consistency`, `round_trip`, and `boundary_crossing`.\n   203\t\n   204\tSystem scoring is intended to count a failure only when a downstream public projection diverges after the relevant local primitive behavior has been established. Counter auto-creation and `lrange` on missing keys are local contracts covered by unit tests; system cases use counters that already exist and test post-delete/flush list behavior through fresh type reuse rather than repeating the missing-key `lrange` primitive.\n   205\t\n"}], "is_error": false, "command": "view", "path": "G:\\research\\01_agents\\swe-e2e\\Bmk-dev\\task\\minikv-realrepo-submit\\prd.md", "prev_exist": true, "old_content": null, "new_content": null, "kind": "FileEditorObservation"}, "action_id": "84662b7b-c0b5-4ddf-bac0-5c7b50e97ebe", "kind": "ObservationEvent"}
